Barack Obama will be the fourth American President to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize, as the fourth American President of history.
The $1.4 million diploma, medal and cheque will receive them, inter alia, for the exceptional effort to strengthen global diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will arrive in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and will have a lot to do.
First, visit to the Nobel Institute, where for the first time you will meet the five members of the committee who, in October, elected you from 172 people to 33 organizations.
Then, the presidential couple has a meeting with the King of Norway, Harald V, and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon the visit will culminate with a ceremony in which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth American president to receive it, although the third one to receive it in his office.
The White House has already announced that, upon receiving the prize, it will talk about the Afghan war.
The President does not want to avoid this subject, knowing that he is receiving the prize as president of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
His war efforts increased even more with the sending of additional troops to Afghanistan, which he did not forget to mention any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, diploma and check of ten million Swedish kroner (approximately 24 million Czech kroner).
It is proposed to give them charitable paraffins, but it has not yet decided which organization in particular.
During his full program, the President and his wife will participate in a banquet to which they will attend, in addition to the Norwegian kings, the Prime Minister and 250 other guests.
Obama from the beginning had a rather reserved attitude towards the prize.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling that he didn't deserve it at all.
He also repeated several times that the prize is not only for him, but for all those who fight for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned that it represents "a challenge to take action".
