USA: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It is funny that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself took for the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his Afghan approach, eagerly awaited, it proved to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only in the same text is the phrase "like in Iraq" used several times, but it did not hesitate to use the title of the Bush declaration of January 2007 for its own statement: "A new way forward".
It was he himself, who three years ago criticized Bush's idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from the civil war, and that criticized him as "an irresponsible and catastrophic decision".
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful, so that today there is no talk of Iraq in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, yet objectively left his successor a much more favourable initial situation than could be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama expects the miracle to be repeated.
Field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan General Operation Stanley McCristal. He, even despite traditional subordinate relations, subjected the indecisive rifles in the White House to a harsh criticism.
He asked 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but nothing better happened to him, so at least he fooled the general over 10,000 military personnel.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself had at least 10,000 previously.
The most problematic thing about Obama's entire strategy seems to be his goal, starting to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and completing this procedure in three years. Obama's whole doctrine generated more questions than the answers he offered.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq's society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is reached.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, if they are used to changing the chief every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin. After him, patriarchal tribal relations will remain.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to confusing relationships, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is "capable of action", a minimum objective of the whole operation, seems very real.
Obama's strategy horizon is shocked by his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to deteriorate and is now about to explode.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing about reality, can believe that the military sent to war so that they "come home soon," will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date of withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will regard it as an indirect declaration of the American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans are increasingly less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their voters, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: to try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to look for the answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphal withdrawal of Afghan troops.
However, each such solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left for the presidential elections, and that is why there is still a long time to find another strategy, if this is a total failure.
