A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in the 'hot' HIV virus
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can moderate the spread of HIV in the organism
The main advantage of this improved substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, such as some medicines already accessible.
AIDS can't be cured until now.
However, the life of patients may be significantly prolonged by a mixture of medicines that prevent the replication of HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the virus replication is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, drugs no longer work.
The work of the experts of three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and Heidelberg University demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that substances called metalocarborans have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of HIV.
Metalocarborans are composed of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way different from all medicines used today, and that is why they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists find new, ‘improved' compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the virus albumin.
Metalocarborans have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are joined by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A Traitor and Resistant Virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV proteases, there is no fractionation of the HIV virus and no mature and infectious body cells of the virus would be created.
If we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, explain scientists in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In an article published in the journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds, in which two pairs of cages (see table) are joined by a short organic series, which continues to be systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more effective
The test of the effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was carried out as a test piece, and also against its resistant variants, obtained from HIV patients.
The effect of metalocarborans on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as in clinically used medicines, however they do not lose their effect on resistant variants, in which the drugs often do not work.
The mechanism of the single effect, its other qualities such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications makes, that metalocarborans are interesting compounds for research with the aim of proposing effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína İezáčová, the head of the laboratory of structural biology at the Institute of Organic and Biochemistry Chemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics at the Academy of Sciences.
