Couples who violate politics face huge fines, up to three times their annual salary in some areas, and labour discrimination.
Chinese officials have endorsed the policy for their contribution to avoiding critical pressure on their natural resources, while human rights defenders have denounced abuses in the imposition of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women with a second child to undergo abortions.
In addition, many couples have performed abortions according to the sex of the fetus, leading to an unnatural high male-female ratio.
In recent years, demographic officials have gradually softened their position on single-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule, including urban residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases where both husband and wife are single children, and in 2007 they attenuated many of their hard-line slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Demographic Research at the University of Beijing, said that central government officials have recently been discussing even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the spouses is a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
Almost at night in the morning, the posters ordering families to have only one child were replaced by copies of regulations detailing who would be suitable for having a second child and how to apply for a permit.
The city government sent family planning officials and volunteers to visit couples in their homes and slide brochures under the doors.
He has also promised to provide emotional and financial guidance to those who have chosen to have more than one child.
Family planning officials say that the response has been very unsurprising.
Disappointing response
Although rural city officials outside Shanghai argue that they observed a moderate increase in requests for couples who want a second child after the campaign was launched, the most urban districts do not indicate any change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, is still receiving only four to five applications per month.
The disappointed Shanghai officials say that, despite the campaign, it is still expected that the number of births in the city in 2010 will reach only about 165,000, slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the Caolu Municipality's family planning committee in Shanghai, said financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don't want children anymore.
They want to give their first son the best, he said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and are legally qualified to do so.
But like many Chinese, they have only insufficient health and life insurance provided by the government.
Without a social protection network, they argue, that option would be irresponsible.
People in the West missee the one-child policy as a matter of rights," said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the first child of the couple.
Yeah, we're being robbed of the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just a political issue.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their doubts.
Wang, the human resources manager, said he wants a single child because she too was: "We were the center of our families and we were used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to caring for others and we really do not want to care for others. "
Chen Zijian, 42 years old, owner of a translation agency, explained it more strongly.
For parents with two races, middle class, who reduce the birth rate, he said, it's about having enough success to be selfish.
People aged 20 to 30 grew up watching their parents' struggle during the first days of China's experiment with capitalism and do not want that kind of life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child takes a lot of time from parents, he said.
A mother has to give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are issues of space, "must remodel your apartment," and the strategic "must have a curriculum prepared for the best day care when the child is 9 months old."
Most of his friends are willing to face this once, Chen said, but not two.
Ours is the first generation with the highest standard of living, he said.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, characterized so far by challenging positions and mutual recriminations, caught renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that foresees ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Developed by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not speak of how much money rich countries would give to the poor to face global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, which include how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit of the overall temperature increase that political strategists would be willing to tolerate.
This gives a lot of flexibility to the process," said John Coequyt, senior representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Bóer, described as "the great panorama."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 between 25 and 45 per cent, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their emissions during the same period between 15 and 30 per cent.
Together, countries would cut emissions between 50 and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union also encouraged the talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
However, Friday presented the same kind of verbal fireworks that have dominated the talks last week.
The United States Special Climate Envoy, Todd Stern, rejected claims that require mandatory greenhouse gas emission cuts for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is adopting a tougher line with China, with respect to what the Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States will not agree without major developing countries moving forward and taking action, Stern said, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs of China He Yafei, stated that the top climate negotiator in the United States lacked "common sense", or was "very irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the United States would not help China economically to cope with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the major powers of the world at stake, fault lines have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries in the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it is not surprising that the major powers are discussing who should cost the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in seeking to contain the big emitters responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is being developed, Ulate said, who also works as a regional climate change adviser for International Conservation in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the major participants say that the talks will produce a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, with 43 members, prepared a 24-page preliminary treaty proposal early on Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who leads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the push of small island nations "has put political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now unified and demand the action of emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the exceptional issues before the heads of government close a deal.
High-level officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister, descended from the planes and ran to the halls of the Bella Center, to closed meetings and press conferences, to be able to define the claims that will be arbitrated in the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where each day 13,000 people enter and leave the convention center, the activists who play guitar present night shows mocking the countries that they say are being sold, and preliminary hand-to-hand proposals are passed instead of mail), poses a challenge.
The intensity only builds: almost all key ministers are here right now, and on Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues," said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, vice president for the global policy of International Conservation.
Heavy weights are coming.
The first train to 225 km/h from Britain redefines that Monday feeling
At 5.13 a.m. on Monday morning, a whistle will pierce the darkness to signal a train departure that marks a revolution for travel in Britain.
The country's first high-speed long-distance train will reach 225 km/h, when it passes like lightning from Ashford, Kent, to St Panrcas Station in London, covering 93 kilometres in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Secretary of Transport, will then be joined by Lady Kelly Holmes, on board the first Javelin intercity service outside London.
He hopes that the new service will finally connect Britain to an international network of fast, reliable trains and connect the great conurbations of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
The neglected remote areas would become prosperous suburbs, business travel times would be shortened and the change of aircraft and cars to rail would reduce national coal emissions, as well as ease congestion on roads.
In theory, the three main political parties believe in this vision.
But the tens of billions of pounds that are needed to build a new national rail network, the inevitable battle of planning and fears about environmental damage, can still slow Britain's high-speed lines.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company created in January to provide the government with a feasibility study, will deliver its report to Lord Adonis on December 30, according to the Times.
This will provide you with a detailed itinerary of the next planned stage for the high-speed network.
The new line linking London to the Midlands of the West will be drawn within a five-metre radius in urban areas and areas where environmental impact can be controversial.
In rural areas, the plan will be drawn within a radius of 25 metres of a definitive route.
It is also expected that HS2 will set up three options for a wider high-speed network heading north.
Lord Adonis will answer in spring.
The preferred option that is being proposed is a Y-shaped configuration, in which a single high-speed line would reach the Midlands of the West.
The line would be divided into or near Birmingham, with a branch heading west from the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland, and another to the northeast to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line would enter Scotland.
"It seems that this will be the most beneficial option," said a member of the railway.
Once completed, travel times between London and Edinburgh would be reduced to 2 hours and 40 minutes.
The first stage, which would not be opened before 2025, would allow passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to just over an hour today.
The proposals would allow trains to travel at 402 km/h, making the British network the fastest in Europe.
The initial track is designed to withstand trains of 400 mt in length, capable of transporting 1,100 people.
At least 18 trains could operate every hour on a London-Birmingham line.
This means that a London terminal capable of receiving 20,000 passengers per hour would be needed.
Considering the space constraints of the capital, it is expected that an existing station will be expanded to fit the high-speed network.
The experts from the railway industry argue that only St Pancras International or Euston stations offer that potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether he believes the scheme should proceed, but a broad public consultation and planning procedures mean that no final decision will be taken until after a general election.
Even if it starts the work, the network would have to be built in sections.
In the beginning, trains would be forced to leave fast lines along the existing lanes north of Birmingham, maintaining travel times between London and Scotland over three hours.
This is considered the crucial point necessary to ensure a change of aircraft to trains, a point of reference for the railway revolution.
