Management revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of the big French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with regard to their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of employees joining "values" determined from above as before it was a question of imposing on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer in the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to the strategies of conquering markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to the customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
Demobilization of employees can end in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R & D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, the IB (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have proactive behaviour and a forward-looking vision"; it needs a commitment on the part of employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we call for a management revolution, which would consist of putting the employees at the centre of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as Orange's questionnaire among his employees, incite the management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many turns, all the companies end up doing essentially... what they always did! B989
Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanical way.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old conductist theory that American "neurosciences" recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely spread behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of the commitment of the executives, a recent investigation of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms to managers in a position of mechanistic management, inadequate to the world today.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies means adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating in any reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to become a reality of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the Motivational Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
The studies showed that they judge their company on the basis of a predetermined twofold that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of mobilization factors, business managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate the management of human resources "in the place".
In this way, they create a favourable ground for the organized development of strong and effective business intelligence.
Oslo speech: for the "just war" Obama receives praise from the right
This Friday, the American right, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize has defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States, hailed Obama's speech on Thursday.
The Conservatives, who had discredited Obama's award on 9 October, applauded the presidential speech this time, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate during the 2008 elections.
I loved what she said, said Mrs Palin, the main figure of the right wing of the Republican party to the newspaper USA Today, and added that she herself had addressed the issue of war "sometimes necessary" in her recently published memoirs.
In my opinion, war is, of course, the last thing Americans want to be forced to do, but it is necessary.
Terrorists must be stopped, he noted.
Obama, who inherited the two wars of his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, dedicated himself, this Thursday in Oslo, to justifying the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send 30,000 more soldiers to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another Obama opponent, Newt Gingrich, considered that the president had done "a very good job" in Oslo.
I think the speech was really good, the former Speaker of the House of Representatives was delighted, who appreciated in particular the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential words.
For the moment, the speech seemed very historic to me, Gingrich said, during an interview on the radio program "The Takeaway".
The former elected representative, whom some consider to be a possible candidate for the 2012 presidential election, was pleased to hear "a left-wing president" when he reminded the members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free or could deliver a peace prize if the use of force did not exist".
According to Michael Gerson, author of George W. Bush's speeches and current chronicler at the Washington Post, Obama delivered "a very American speech."
In addition to presenting as a "citizen of the world", as "always does," "he spoke as an American president" by reminding Europeans "who live in a security bubble that they did not create and do not do much to preserve it," Gerson said.
Among the few unconvinced rightwings, a hawk of the Bush era, former UN ambassador John Bolton, described the speech as "monotonous, pretentious and uninspired" on the website of the National Review Online.
To the President's left, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich was alarmed by seeing Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
When we cover the war with the notion of justice, it is easy to justify the massacre of innocent people, he warned.
However, the left-wing press praised the president.
Los Angeles Time, although he still believes that Obama received the Nobel Prize prematurely, described his speech as "superproduction" especially for a speaker known for his talent.
Oslo's speech "should serve as a road map to guide international decisions in the fight against conflict, poverty and oppression," said the Californian newspaper.
Obama "pronounced the speech that was needed," the New York Times estimated, judging it "both gloomy and uplifting."
Road transport: three marathon negotiations to ensure Christmas supply
After three sessions of marathon negotiations, the unions in the road sector and the TLF (Transport and Logistics of France), the only employers' organization that remained until the end, arrived on Friday afternoon at an agreement that puts an end to the strike slogan and the threat to Christmas supply.
During the signing session on Friday night, the Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, was "enjoyed" by the agreement, after several negotiating sessions that began on Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions, the negotiators fired at the dawn of Friday in the hope of quickly signing the text according to the last hour of the morning.
Even though three employers' organizations (FNTR, Unostra, OTHER) withdrew by giving a doorknob.
But a meeting of more than six hours that began at 11 a.m. was necessary for everyone to agree and the text was signed at 6 p.m.
The conflict "had been very damaging to companies" and "we were afraid it would disturb the end of the year parties," Bussereau said.
The text provides for an increase of 4 per cent for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport) and 2.9 per cent for the highest (international transport).
The hourly rate rises from 8,72 euros to 9,06 for low wages.
Not much, but we started with a lot of disadvantage, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
If so, we will order our militants that there will be no more cuts or blockades in the supply centres.
But there can always be some disgruntled rebel, he added.
