It is a common sense agreement that respects employees, said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) recognized it as "a historic agreement".
For Richard Jaubert (CGT) it is "an acceptable commitment".
The agreement also provides for an increase in travel costs of 3 per cent and the holding of general assemblies of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will, above all, address the issue of extraordinary pay and modernization of the collective agreement.
Bussereau recalled that "a decrease of EUR 100 million in employer charges" was the subject of an amendment by the government to the draft law on rectification finance for 2009, which the National Assembly voted on Thursday night.
The government will ask the Senate to vote "under the same terms".
TLF's signature allows the agreement to apply, first, to companies affiliated to TLF and, secondly, to the entire profession, in case the Minister of Labour makes an extension.
It will be done "as soon as possible", said Bussereau.
The opposition of employers' organizations could only delay the process.
The FNTR reported that it was a "business of naïves", since the EUR 100 million "had already been promised to the sector to compensate for part of the CO2 tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate in a situation of urgency, not as a conclusion to an analysis discussed by the parties, but not to contradict those who want to eat turkey at the next dinner in Nochebuena, the Unestra regretted.
For the OTHER, the agreement puts at risk "the stability of a lot of SMEs in the sector over the next 12 months".
