Turkish Justice Dissolves Prokurdo Party, a Decision with Serious Consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled on Friday in favour of the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that immediately provoked demonstrations of anger in the Kurdish community, in the south-eastern part of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the government's task, which has just helped the Kurdish community by trying to put an end to 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society (DTP) party was dissolved because it had become the "focus of activities that adversely affected the independence of the State and its indivisible unity," the President of the Court, Hasim Kiliç, told the press after four days of discussion.
The decision of the 11 judges was unanimous, although only a majority of seven votes were needed to obtain the dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party's leaders, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, are out of political life for five years.
The judge also announced the cessation of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Türk and Tugluk, and the confiscation of the party's assets by the Treasury.
The DTP has 21 benches in Parliament (550).
Its leaders warned before the verdict that Members would leave Parliament before being party-based parliamentarians.
The decision follows a procedure launched by the Supreme Court Prosecutor, Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, in 2007, accusing DTP of obeying the "principles" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many more countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
However, the party claims that it does not have "organic links" with the PKK, but refuses to qualify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The verdict of the Court intervenes at the time when the government lends a hand to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen their rights, so that the Kurds stop supporting the PKK and thus end the conflict.
DTP leaders stated that a dissolution could lead to an increase in tensions in the Southeast anatoll, where a large number of demonstrations against the conditions of detention of PKK chief Abdullah Öcalan degenerated into clashes with the police over the past few weeks.
Since the announcement of justice, thousands of protesters have gathered in front of DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the great city of the Southeast mostly inhabited by Kurds.
The Forces of the Order threw tear grenades and used water cannons, while the protesters threw Molotov bombs or stones with hoops.
In Istanbul, approximately 100 people were also concentrated.
After the verdict, Türk stated that the decision of justice was to "deepen the discouragement".
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (Kurda, NDLR) by dissolving a party, it told the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also regrets the decision.
At first we oppose the closure of parties.
This is not how anything is resolved, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision completely boycotts the democratic openness launched by the government, said political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
This Thursday, the PKK was awarded an attack in which seven soldiers died three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the most bloody attacks of recent months.
Snows can start suddenly
