The birthplace of the dinosaur
The Tawa found had the same appearance as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal of two meters long and 1.50 meters high running on the two strong back legs, had an extended head with sharp teeth and curves, short arms with claws in the shape of a hole and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, it would not have been something special.
But the Tawa found was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry area of the Pangea supercontinent in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavation in 2006 at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes, we have found on a day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis a member of the Utah Natural History Museum team.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they gathered in total the remains of five specimens.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional finding: "The dinosaur fossils of the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not fully share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current trend of opinion, dinosaurs first appeared approximately 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these first dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, the experts discuss, for example, when the sarians divided into their three most important genealogical lines: the carnivorous teropods among the Tyrannosaurus Rex, Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the herbivorous Ornithischia (sauri with bird pelvis), to which, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus belong.
According to Nesbitt's analysis and colleagues, Tawa finds himself a primitive therapist.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in Tawa's skull, researchers found signs of air bags, such as those that also possess the descendants of the teropods, birds.
Thanks to air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa, the bones of the spine were evidently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive airbag therapist, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the posterior giant sauropods also had air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known lived in South America, researchers deduce that the sarians first emerged there.
Therefore, the three genealogical lines were separated at the beginning and extended from South America throughout all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single earthly mass, the Pangea supercontinent.
However, the facts say that the team found together with Tawa finds the remains of two other teropods not closely related.
The three cannot descend from a single parent predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three migration waves were given to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a brotherly group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says the paleontologist of Bonn Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many fossils of dinosaurs continue to be preserved, while in other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs evolved from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic the dinosaurs still shared their vital space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and pterosauruses and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs expanded all over the world and developed many new species, while the kinship was extinguished at the limit of the Triassic towards the Jurasic.
The successful stories were not eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a massive extinction that dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, an impact of meteorite brake the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
