In a state of vigilance, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the case of mentally ill and drug addicts do the boundaries between imagination and reality fade.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we are lying in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can give ourselves unhindered to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, anyone who experiences sleep-like states during vigil, or sees and hears things that others don't see or hear, is most often regarded in the modern Western world as crazy or drug addict, or at least as manic.
But such images and voices not only arise in the mentally ill or in the drug addicts.
Guilt has our imagination: the same neuronal processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, sometimes make the boundaries between sleep, madness and reality unravel.
One-way modified states of consciousness can appear in the most diverse forms, in the best of cases we call them visions, and in the worst, madness.
Although the triggers and effects can be distinguished, the visions of mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the prophet of the New Age Carlos Castañeda, the states of Chamanic possession, and psychosis and hallucinations can be referred to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neural communication substances in the brain has been derailed – especially dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine – and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disturbed.
During schizophrenic psychosis, complex hallucinations and crazy thoughts often occur.
