Emergency braking aid is already compulsory
As with anti-locking ABS brakes and will pass with ESP stability control, emergency braking systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all passenger cars and light commercial vehicles of new registration, while for the rest a period of absence is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, by its way of work, it can also help to avoid many collisions by scope.
The emergency braking assistant does what it does is to increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the treadmill that the driver gives.
But this does not always keep that pressure to the end.
According to a study carried out by the manufacturer of Bosch car components, the third of the drivers involved in an accident had not come to tread the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance the car uses to stop.
According to an EU study itself, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided per year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four accidents with damage to people would be avoided - when so-called intelligent emergency braking systems are popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps to increase the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device exerts the utmost effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
